Kultur spielt eine bedeutende Rolle in jeder Verhandlung. Kultur kann vielmehr durch das, was sie nicht ist, als durch das, was sie ist und was sie bedeutet, definiert werden. Kultur ist nicht homogen, sondern ein spezifisches Ding. Sie ist auch nicht singular oder einheitlich. Aussagen wie “alle Russen sind stur” oder “alle Japaner sind gutmütig” sind inhärent weit gefasst und zu einfach. Während die allgemeine Erkenntnis über eine Kultur.productiv für einen Verhandler ist, ist es viel produktiver, zu verstehen, wie wichtig die Kultur im jeweiligen Kontext ist und wie diese Einstellung die Gespräche beeinflussen wird. Wenn man eine fremde Kultur kennenlernt, erlebt man sie auf eine Weise, die mit der eigenen Kultur vergleichbar ist, und Vergleiche sind zwangsläufig. Verstehen einer fremden Kultur oder Mentalität kann von der Untersuchung ihrer Geschichte bis zur Erfassung ihrer Vorurteile reichen. Statt zu urteilen oder zu versuchen, eine Kultur zu ändern, muss man sie einfach so akzeptieren, wie sie ist, und innerhalb ihrer Grenzen arbeiten, besonders im Rahmen von Verhandlungen, insbesondere wenn man mit einer schwächeren Verhandlungsposition an den Tisch kommt. Ähnlich wie ein Verhandler sich in “fremdem” Gelände befindet, kann Respekt vor Traditionen und Überzeugungen nur helfen, kulturelle Barrieren zu überwinden und die Verhandlung voranzutreiben.

Es ist wichtig zu beachten, dass Kultur sich nicht unbedingt auf eine national/internationale Dichotomie beschränkt. Die meisten Unternehmen innerhalb einer gegebenen Nation entwickeln ihre eigene Unternehmenskultur. Zum Beispiel könnte eine Unternehmenskultur lange Arbeitszeiten am Arbeitsplatz oder eine entspanntere Arbeitszeit betonen. Ein Zeichen einer Unternehmenskultur kann in der Dresscode der Mitarbeiter, im Kommunikationsstil (direkte vs. indirekte Kommunikation, Delegation von Aufgaben) und in den Einstellungsverfahren sichtbar sein. Einige Unternehmen fördern Philanthropie auf jeder Ebene der Mitarbeiter, andere beschränken sie auf “genehmigte” Wohltätigkeitsorganisationen oder Spendenaktionen. Man muss nur die Unterschiede in der amerikanischen Unternehmenskultur von Unternehmen zu Unternehmen (und sogar innerhalb eines Unternehmens von Region zu Region, einschließlich städtischer zu suburbanen Umgebungen) betrachten, um die Vielfalt der Gedanken zu schätzen, die in einer bestimmten gesellschaftlichen Kultur wohnen können. Einige Kulturen sind nicht annähernd so geschichtet wie die amerikanische Kultur und erscheinen einem Außenstehenden möglicherweise einheitlicher, aber ein ähnliches Äußeres ist ein Zeichen, tiefer zu graben.

Werte sind jedoch noch wichtiger zu verstehen, weil sie den Grund einer Kultur liefern. Wenn das Ersparen von Gesicht oder die soziale Harmonie innerhalb einer Kultur geschätzt wird, ist es sicher, dass ein Verhandler seinen Konzern oder seine Vorgesetzten nicht öffentlich beschämen wird, um am Verhandlungstisch zu gewinnen. Ein Verhandler aus einer Kultur, die einen harten Verhandlungsstil höher schätzt, wird möglicherweise nicht versucht sein, sich zu früh zu einigen. Diese Allgemeinheiten in Betracht zu ziehen, ist wichtig, bevor man sich an den Verhandlungstisch setzt. Ein Verhandler ist jedoch gut beraten, etwas über seinen Gegner auf persönlicher Ebene zu erfahren, um die Verhandlung effektiv zu gestalten.

"Der Narr hat in seinem Herzen gesagt: 'Es gibt keinen Gott.' Diese Worte finden sich zuerst in Psalm 14 der christlichen Bibel und sind der Anfang des Arguments von St. Anselm zur Existenz Gottes. Diese Überzeugung scheint auch von dem anderen Autor, Thomas Aquinas, geteilt zu werden, den wir diskutieren werden. Da beide ihre Argumente zur Verteidigung desselben Konzepts vorbringen und unsere Aufgabe darin besteht zu bestimmen, welches der beiden besser ist, müssen wir aus Gründen der Kürze voraussetzen, dass beide in ihrer Überzeugung von der Existenz Gottes, specifically des Gottes der Bibel, recht haben. Ein Gott-Typ-Figur, die nicht dem entspricht, an den unsere beiden Autoren glauben, würde uns nicht gestatten, ihre beiden Argumente adäquat zu vergleichen, da sie im Wesentlichen zur Verteidigung einer bestimmten Gotteskonzept vorgebracht werden. Dass gesagt, würde ich vorschlagen, dass beide valide Punkte anbringen, aber keines von ihnen eine umfassende Grundlage für den Glauben an Gott bietet.

Um diesen Punkt zu veranschaulichen, werden wir zunächst das grundlegende Argument von St. Anselm untersuchen. Anselms Passage beschreibt einen Weg des Verständnisses durch den Glauben, indem man in sich selbst nach Beweisen für Gott sucht. Er erklärt, dass Gott in unserem Verständnis existiert und wir daher seine Nichtexistenz nicht effektiv konzipieren können. Während dieser Gedanke, wenn er in seinen Begriffen ausformuliert ist, etwas umständlich und manchmal unklar ist, läuft es letztlich darauf hinaus, dass der Beweis für Gott in unserem eigenen Verstand zu finden ist. St. Anselm suggeriert uns, dass wir nicht über die Grenzen unserer eigenen Seele hinausgehen müssen, um die Wahrheit über Gott zu finden, sondern dass die Existenz dieses Wesens einfach durch die Untersuchung dessen, was wir in unserem eigenen Verstand für wahr halten, als wahr erachtet wird. Externe Beweise sind angeblich nicht notwendig. Diese Idee, die Annahme dessen, was nicht durch eine unumstößliche empirische Evidenzbasis bewiesen werden kann, wird in christlichen Texten oft als Glaube bezeichnet.

Diese Vorstellung unterscheidet sich stark von der von St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas hingegenargumentiert, dass die Existenz Gottes vollständig durch Vernunft und empirische Beweise bewiesen werden kann, ohne dass Glaube vonnöten ist. Eine solche Idee wäre vorteilhaft für die Missionierung, einem wichtigen Element des Christentums, da sie die Gewinung neuer Konvertierten ohne Abhängigkeit von ihrer Bereitschaft ermöglichen würde, etwas zu akzeptieren, das nicht bewiesen werden kann. Sie könnten stattdessen allein durch Logik überzeugt werden. St. Thomas führt fünf verschiedene logische Argumente zur Unterstützung der Existenz Gottes an:Change, Kausalität, Kontingenz, Grade von Exzellenz und Harmonie. In jedem Fall zeigt er im Grunde, dass der Beweis für Gott in der logischen Notwendigkeit für Gott liegt. Wenn man dir sagt, dass dir ein Puzzleteil fehlt und du das restliche Puzzle zusammensetzt, legt Logik nahe, dass du die Merkmale und die Existenz des fehlenden Teils kennen kannst, ohne ihn sehen zu müssen."

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would later be known as Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and attained enlightenment, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism, the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is about twenty-five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen throughout, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laypeople alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run the gamut from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.

There are several qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force originating from members of the Buddha-sasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force born of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.

First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one escape Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laypeople, there are five precepts (I will not kill, I will not lie, I will not steal, I will not engage in inappropriate sexual behavior, and I will not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

Die USA und Mexiko sind ein Beispiel für zwei Nationen, die einst von einer anhaltenden Rivalität geplagt waren, die sich von 1836 bis 1893 erstreckte. Der Höhepunkt dieser Rivalität war der Mexikanisch-Amerikanischen Krieg von 1846 bis 1848, in dem die Vereinigten Staaten gegen Mexiko kämpften und Texas sowie den amerikanischen Südwesten als neues Territorium annektierten. Es gab zahlreiche weitere Auseinandersetzungen zwischen den beiden Nationen, die sich bis kurz vor dem Ersten Weltkrieg legten. Die Rivalität begann, als Amerikaner und Mexikaner auf wichtige Fragen wie Religion, Kultur und Tradition stießen und einen grundlegenden Interessenkonflikt hatten (Schmitt 1974 S. 30-31).
Dies ist nicht unähnlich vielen anderen Nationen, die eine langanhaltende Rivalität mit einem Nachbarland haben. Nationen, die eine Grenze teilen, neigen dazu, Interessenkonflikte zu haben, die zu rivalisierenden Positionen zwischen den Nationen führen. Die USA und Mexiko sind nicht unähnlich vielen anderen langanhaltenden Rivalitäten zwischen Nachbarn. David M. Pletcher (1977) stellt fest: „Nur in Mexiko und Kuba findet man langanhaltende, übergreifende amerikanische diplomatische Probleme“ (S. 41). Tatsächlich sind beide Nationen geografisch nah an den USA und waren Rivalen der USA, während andere lateinamerikanische Nationen gute Beziehungen zu den USA pflegten.
Religiöse Fragen trieben einen Keil zwischen die beiden Nationen, was viele Nationen im Laufe der Geschichte betraf. Sally Frahm (2001) stellt fest: „Waren die Amerikaner im 20. Jahrhundert gegen Faschismus und Kommunismus, standen sie im 18. und 19. Jahrhundert gegen Katholizismus und Monarchie“ (S. 86). Ähnlich wie die Rivalität zwischen den USA und der Sowjetunion während des Kalten Kriegs sowohl ideologische als auch Interessenkonflikte umfasste, war hier die ideologische Rivalität nicht auf die politische Struktur, sondern auf die religiösen Vorlieben der USA und Mexikos zurückzuführen. Dieses Misstrauen wuchs aus dem Misstrauen zwischen Engländern und Spaniern heran. Diesegefühle des Misstrauens, die sie von ihren ehemaligen kolonialen Herrschern geerbt hatten, stellte eine erhebliche Barriere für die Etablierung freundschaftlicher Beziehungen zwischen den USA und Mexiko dar.
Diehl und Goerts (2000) listen 17 Streitigkeiten zwischen Mexiko und den USA während der 57-jährigen Rivalität auf. Die meisten Streitigkeiten, die Diehl und Goerts während der Rivalitätszeit beschreiben, betreffen territoriale Fragen, insbesondere Grenzübergriffe von mexikanischem Gebiet in die USA und andere Grenzprobleme. Grenzübergriffe durch Banditen und Gesetzlose aus amerikanischen Grenzstädten waren ein großes Problem, das anhielt, bis sowohl die USA als auch Mexiko militärische Gewalt an ihren Grenzen einsetzten (Schmitt 1974 S. 97).
Schmitt (1974) erklärt, dass die Rivalität zwischen den beiden Nationen nachließ, als „Mexiko in einem erheblichen Maße von den USA abhängig wurde“ (S. 109) und schließlich endete, als amerikanische Ambitionen „von territorialer Expansion zu wirtschaftlicher Intervention in Mexico“ (S. 110) im späteren 19. Jahrhundert schwenkten.

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed.

I was a nurse at the time. I chose this profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick" was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So—even though my dream was to be a scientist or journalist—preferably a little of both—I chose nursing.

Nevertheless, there I was: 46 years old and single, no money in the bank to speak of, and unable to work. To this day I am disabled, and after 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I have literally nothing left that I can call "mine." I get by, but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, yet, there is one thing that I know to be true: I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends, no matter how strong I was. And believe me, when real disaster strikes, you do not feel very strong at all.

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life—big and small. There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares, some things are just too big to overcome on your own.

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's "basket"; Lord knows it is moldy and falling apart, anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again—learning to help each other and to ask for help—rather than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters.

The Conservatives in the US talk about the "rugged individualism" that built this country; but in truth, what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism, it was compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit; first aid supplies, water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries, lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods, too. If you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food—do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove, as long as you do not live in an apartment.

But while you are at it, get to know your neighbors.

Why do organisms evolve as they do? Are there any restrictions or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? While D’Arcy Thompson in 1917 stated that "Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," the same can be said today. Recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study is exploring how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic change in Prunum, in combination with experimental studies, can be used to elucidate the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to delineate quantitative parameters that could in turn be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were entered into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could be used to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a structure that is a tube that travels through 360 degrees of space over time. These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl and is referred to as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl of a shell is the last whorl (body whorl). The spire is considered to be all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire and the opposite end is referred to as the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical, basal, apertural and abapertural views. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture toward the viewer and the apex pointing up.)

A method for counting whorls is as follows: First, view the shell from the apical view and determine where the first suture begins. Draw a line dividing the shell into two parts. Count whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal accretes (i.e., builds) its shell. It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is made, it is then possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia has remained relatively constant over the past ten years.  Although the country is on track to meet many of the Millennium Development Goals, such as the water and sanitation targets, the improvements in child and maternal health are far from adequate to meet their target goals by 2015.  The reasons for these shortcomings will be discussed below, indicating a need to strengthen the healthcare system rather than focusing on programmatic interventions.
	Indonesia has made progress in the number of births attended by skilled healthcare workers, with 72% meeting this target.  However, this figure includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot provide medical interventions in case of complications, leading to a high percentage of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage.  In other words, the improvements in this indicator are somewhat deceptive, and there is still much work to be done.  Additionally, there has been a decrease in the percentage of under-five children's diarrhea cases treated by healthcare professionals.  While data on postnatal care is incomplete, it is clear that this area is also a concern, with low rates across the country.
	C-section rates remain lower than expected, at around 4%.  This also highlights another worrying issue.  While the rate is 7% in urban areas, it is only 2% in rural areas, indicating inequity in healthcare access.  Clearly, healthcare services are primarily focused in urban areas.  Another access-related issue is vertical equity, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, making it much harder for the poor to access healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.
	When considering the next steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the most fundamental question is how to best address the lack of services.  Specifically, should Indonesia focus on program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall healthcare system without prioritizing pre- and postnatal care for mothers and children?  There's no doubt that programmatic approaches to tackle the issues outlined above are appealing.  Not only do "vertical approaches" targeting one sector of improvements have more precise, manageable objectives, but they also typically yield faster results.  However, there are some drawbacks to consider.  One major drawback is that investing heavily in programming for one particular health sector may lead to funding shortages in other areas, and human resources may concentrate on the better-resourced sectors (as seen in the impact of international HIV/AIDS funding on the family planning sector).  Additionally, running multiple parallel programs for one area can result in duplicated services that are not coordinated between programs, leading to increased paperwork and bureaucracy for supplies and funding.

Victorian novels are characterized by their overwhelming attention to detail and their focus on the aristocracy of the period. Two novels that stray away from this tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both novels employ an element of mystery and a flair for the bizarre, atypical of the novels from the period, which strengthens the characters within each work; providing insight that elaborates on their motives and emotions.

A couple of years ago, I worked in an after-school program tutoring elementary-aged students. I did my best to help them in whatever subject they were struggling in, but my strengths were in English and reading. I was recruited by one of the instructors to help a young boy named Adrian (I believe he was in third or fourth grade) who was having a lot of trouble reading. It hit me that something was wrong; he had the most peculiar problems. Some letters he understood how to pronounce perfectly, others not even close, it was the strangest thing. You know, he was of Latino descent, that I was sure, but the boy spoke perfect English. We struggled until the day I met his mother. I was babysitting a few stragglers while the rest of the after-school group was on a field trip when his mother walked in. His mother didn't speak a word of English, only Spanish. With my very basic knowledge of Spanish (I had just started learning it), we managed to communicate. But it was then that it hit me like a sack of bricks: Adrian could read fine, he just didn't know the English alphabet very well. I don't know if that revelation ever helped him much, but I do hope that he's doing better now.

I tell that story to address the problem of the language barrier in schools, especially here in California. I also tell it to prove that it's not always as obvious as we'd think. Even for a child who speaks perfect English, reading can still be a huge obstacle. I think everyone can agree that this problem exists, so what do we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was fairly simple: tutoring in English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciations. But for the many children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There is no one answer. The key lies in combining all of the above!

First of all, the dual language system is a great idea. Not just for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. “Children in two-way bilingual education programs have been found to outperform their peers academically.” There's a lot of fear surrounding this idea, that it's a waste of resources, and that the majority of children in schools will reap no benefit. But that's false. If we were to apply these sorts of programs in the classroom as the rule, rather than the exception, all children would benefit from it. How do we go about this though? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? No. That would be unreasonable and slightly unrealistic. However, I do think that there is no reason we can't have special aids, tutors, whatever you want to call them, who are bilingual.

From the moment we are children, most of us are told that there is something out there that is bigger than us, bigger than we can comprehend. Some of us are sent to Sunday school to learn about it, while others go to church or search within ourselves for the answers. Many of us readily accept the religions that have been passed down to us by our parents. However, some of us reject them firmly, denying that there can be nothing beyond our own personal egocentric universe. We may adopt one value structure only to later change our minds and value another in its place. Whatever path we choose, we journey to define a part of ourselves through our own unique perspectives of spirituality. We search for a light in the dark to lead us out of the shadows and into the sun.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked him what his favorite type of bird was. We sat on the front porch of our house, listening to the rain pound on the tin roof overhead while we smoked our cigarettes together. The gutters brought the rain down, drowning the plants along the edge of the porch. He looked out into the rain, with a gaze that seemed half searching, half remembering. He had grown thinner over the past few months, and his clothes hung listlessly from his body. His hair was thinner, sparser than I remembered it. He stared out into the rain still, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, afraid, and unable to talk to my father about how much I would miss him because talking about it would only make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair a little closer to his, and joined him in gazing out into the falling rain of the June twilight.

My father passed away in December that year, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation had not eased my father’s suffering, but kept him alive a few more months past the doctors’ projections; what the value was when he merely suffered longer I could not define. What kind of God would do this, I thought to myself. Alone in the night, I said no prayers. If God existed, I thought, he had stopped listening to me long ago.

I had not wanted to watch him pass from this life into another one. So I had not. I could not watch the life that created me while it ended. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived and not how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than they did, better than his family did, and knew Dad would not wish for his only child to be a spectator at his death. I curled up in a ball in my bed for three days and waited for the news.

No one even called me.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is, in essence and name, an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" as Ian Watt describes it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic mode has been both criticized and praised, accused of lacking depth and celebrated for the 'terrible sublime' it evokes (Burke). The original "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, blended ideas from both "ancient and modern" romances to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new form of literary expression. Walpole incorporated "old" theatrical elements and 'new' mimicry of nature in 'modern' novels to present what he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre draws heavily on medieval Gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even at the time of The Castle of Otranto's publication, the word "gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and epochs, often viewed as archaic or unsophisticated in the face of "modern" societal and literary advancements. The combination of the more theatrical "Gothic" and the novel's new format, which granted readers a more personal view of characters' psychologies, allowed the Gothic genre to endure and remain both obsolete and new to readers removed from the original timeline.

One of the most prominent Gothic ideas in Gothic novels is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, the process of training a proper knight, is both preserved and transformed in the original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is particularly important to Gothic writers because it embodied the ideal of the classic knight—brave, honorable, and competent—and because they perceived a lack of this ideal in contemporary society. Through chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" becomes idealized and romanticized, hinting at the genre's future evolution towards Romanticism and being used to try to improve the present. Writing The Castle of Otranto during a politically tumultuous time, Walpole may have felt despair over society's potential future and lamented the loss of the supposed morality and inherent "goodness" evident in the Gothic era. This is evident in several characters, including Frederic. Before meeting Frederic, the reader knows he embodies many chivalric traits, as he is described as:

The description includes many traditionally chivalric images; Frederic is, foremost, a prince, has suffered, been suitably affected by tragedy, and is currently thought to have been killed by infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is, of course, exaggerated, introducing the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management is the series of processes for moving goods from customer orders through the raw materials stage, procurement, production, and distribution to the customer. The term supply chain management was coined in 1982 by Keith Oliver, a consultant. Keith Oliver described the overall process of planning, implementing, and controlling what goes on in the supply chain to satisfy customers' needs quickly and efficiently. There are six key elements to a supply chain: production, procurement, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these six key elements to provide the best customer service.

Production is the first step in the supply chain process. Production is the foundation for the entire supply chain process. The production stage outlines when, why, where, and how everything will be produced. Managers need to know what customers want. To find out what customers want, managers can analyze the market. The market is the biggest indicator to determine what the customer demands are. Once managers have analyzed the market and understand customer demand, they are ready to decide what products should be produced and in what quantity. After the management has decided what is produced and how many, they are ready to decide where the products should be produced and at which plant will be best for volume and quality of goods, keeping in mind the customer demand and satisfaction must be met. After the location for production of the products has been decided, the next step is managers' focus on scheduling workloads and maintenance of equipment. Production is a very important step in the supply chain process. Every detail is vital throughout the whole process. If every detail is not planned accordingly, it could cost the company a lot of time and money in the long run. For example, I used to work at Wal-Mart and Target retail stores. Both companies have a design, booklet, and process for every entity of the business. There is a designed layout of how an employee's uniform should look and how to receive shipments from trucks. Having outlined processes allow a company to work smoothly without confusion of direction and expectations.

The second key element in supply chain management is procurement. Procurement is defined as the strategic decisions that should be made to determine the core capabilities of a facility and outsourcing partnerships should grow from these decisions. A company may have many different divisions of production for a single product. All divisions consist of different equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager must decide which division is a best fit for the different processes of the product. Management may also decide to outsource the work to other companies. The core reason a manager would outsource the work to companies is to create velocity. Velocity is the ability to provide quality and flexibility while at the same time reducing costs or maintaining low cost levels.

Hitler lebt in Burma, sagt das Schild.

Ellen Page, die Hauptdarstellerin von Juno, steht allein auf einem Bürgersteigeck und hält ein Stück Karton über ihrem Kopf, auf das sie mit einem Sharpie eine beunruhigende Nachricht geschrieben hat. Burma, auch bekannt als Myanmar, ist ein südostasiatisches Land, das von einer tyrannischen militanten Junta regiert wird, die durch einen Putsch im Jahr 1962 an die Macht gekommen sind. Im Jahr 2007 gab es eine Reihe von Straßenprotesten, die ersten öffentlichen Proteste seit einem Jahrzehnt. Diese Proteste wurden von einer großen Anzahl von burmesischen Mönchen angeführt und trugen den Namen „The Saffron Revolution“, benannt nach der Farbe der Gewänder, die die Mönche trugen. Nach den ersten anfänglichen Aufständen begann die Bevölkerung zunehmend an den Protesten teilzunehmen, und zuerst ließ die burmesische Regierung die Mönche friedliche Versammlungen abhalten. Bald eskalierte die Gewalt jedoch zu einemAusnahmezustand, in dem es zwischen den Mönchen und der Militärjunta zu einer Art Krieg kam, bei dem die Militärjunta Aktivisten und Mönchsgemeinschaften in ganz Burma angriff und plünderte. Ausländische Journalisten wurden festgenommen und inhaftiert, darunter ein japanischer Fotojournalist namens Kenji Nagai, der am 27. September 2007 nur wegen seiner Teilnahme an einem Straßenprotest getötet wurde. Während die offizielle Opferzahl bei 13 liegt, sagte Colonel Hla Win, der einige Tage vor der offiziellen Meldung desertiert war, „Es wurden in den letzten Tagen viele mehr Menschen getötet, als Sie gehört haben. Die Leichen können in mehreren Tausend gezählt werden.“

Das ist nichts Neues. Während diese einige der jüngsten Beispiele für Misshandlungen in unserer Welt sind, ist der Wunsch einer Regierung, Dissent zu unterdrücken und ihre Bürger vollständig zu kontrollieren, so alt wie die Zivilisation selbst. Frühere römische Kaiser erklärten sich selbst zu den von den Göttern Auserwählten, um über jeden Aspekt ihrer Gesellschaft absolute Macht auszuüben. Japanische Kaiser werden als Götter angesehen, die in unsere Welt gesandt wurden, um ihre Menschen zu Wohlstand zu führen, sei es durch die Erfindung von Motorola-Handys oder Hara-kiri, und unser derzeitiger Präsident, George W. Bush, führt wöchentliche Konferenzschaltungen mit Ted Haggard durch, dem Führer von Stupid People Worldwide, einer Untergruppe der Republican Party.

Einige der bekanntesten Beispiele für diese Handlungen sind der 1989er Juni 4. Tiananmen-Platz-Protest, bei dem Intellektuelle, Arbeiteraktivisten und Studenten sich versammelten, um gegen die autoritäre Regierung zu protestieren. Die Opferzahl variiert stark, mit offiziellen Berichten der chinesischen Regierung von 200-300 Toten und Berichten der Chinesischen Roten Kreuzes von 2.000-3.000 Toten. Ein weiteres Beispiel ist der Völkermord in Ruanda in den 1990er Jahren, bei dem Hutu-Milizen, unterstützt von der ruandischen Regierung, systematisch alle Tutsis und politische Gemäßigte töteten, unabhängig von ihrer ethnischen Herkunft. Hitlers „Drittes Reich“, eine Ära, die sich über mehrere Jahre und mehrere Länder erstreckte und bei der jeder mit jüdischen Wurzeln getötet wurde, ist ein weiteres extremes Beispiel.

Duke Ellington’s legacy in jazz comes primarily from his longevity and, by extension, his creative abilities to shape his orchestra. Ellington’s presence on the piano is subtle in many of the compositions selected for this assignment, but as a composer, he excelled at creating rich and complex pieces that highlighted the individual abilities of band members. Ellington crafted the framework in which a soloist could freely improvise, in addition to writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that called on the particular style of band members to highlight musical ideas. In doing this, he also emphasized the tone of the orchestra more generally, creating coherent and original sounds to fit each piece. Ellington’s mastery of the individual players’ sound, as well as how they fit together in a growing ensemble, enabled him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history. The Grove Music dictionary, in discussing Ellington’s sound and innovation, mentions Creole Love Call in reference to using voice “as a jazz instrument” throughout his career. This is an early example of Ellington’s use of voice to add texture and color without the hindrance of lyrics. Creole Love Call also demonstrates Ellington’s ability to compliment the style of his soloists, something that is evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve bar blues piece contains six choruses, as follows: Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice begins smooth and melodic, then transitions to a rougher sound towards the end. Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several extended blue notes. Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase. Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections. Chorus 5: The climactic chorus of the piece, as the reeds now begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections. Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus the voice takes on the sound of the “growl” technique, soloing as an instrument. Tag: Brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone. Ellington’s use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley’s playing and instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington’s orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

She had always felt like she was missing something. This longing could not be satisfied. It began when she was around 14, during her teenage years, and it lingered three years later, at the age of 17. By then, she had resolved that she desired a person rather than a thing. However, she felt no interest in any boys. Some were drawn to her, but their attempts to woo her were in vain. She often pondered this peculiar situation, trying to understand what could cause such a thing with a teenage girl. Over the years, she had formed theories, but nothing concrete. Hence, she continued to live her life, constantly questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were kind and calm. They rarely argued with each other or with their daughter, except when she asserted her independence and free-spirited personality. She was the daughter of calm parents, yet she balanced their serenity with her lively and entertaining nature, making her very likable.

Today, however, was not a peaceful day. As she wandered from room to room, searching for inspiration for her own life, she heard a short scream from the kitchen. Her mother's voice was filled with pain. She rushed in, panic rising, and asked, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She found her mother lying on the floor, groaning, "Ow." The daughter quickly knelt by her side, "Ouch... sweetie, I... need you to take me to the hospital." The words came out rushed and strained, and the daughter could tell her mother was in intense pain. "Okay, Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother directed her hands, and at that moment, the daughter was thankful for her training. She carried her mother to the car, laid her down in the back seat, and drove.

The hospital was filled with the smell of disinfectant and sickness, but the daughter was too focused on helping her mother to feel it. She rushed with her injured mother to the hospital, calling for help. Doctors gathered and quickly brought a stretcher for her mother. They took her away to assess her, leaving the daughter to wait anxiously.

Her mother had fallen off a step stool while attempting to reach a vase from the highest cabinet.

This study demonstrates that adherence to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score", is linked to a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke and stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by a higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains and legumes), monounsaturated fat (compared to saturated fat) and fish, along with a lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol intake is permitted.

Previous prospective studies have documented an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, and an intervention trial showed that the Med diet is more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. Previous studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63 years, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed diet score from self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake over the preceding year. More than 95% of nurses maintained their participation throughout the 20-year period. FFQs were subject to validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD and stroke were confirmed by reviewing medical or hospital records, autopsy or death certificates. Where records were not available, cases were considered "probable" and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging the scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over the course of 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the top aMed quintile were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America experienced a catastrophic financial crisis. Unemployment surged, the housing market imploded, and many of America's largest and most influential corporations were left in ruins. This recession continues to this day, prompting the question: how did this crisis happen, and how can we stop it? In essence, the financial crisis was caused by selfish and naive political decisions that forced banks and companies to issue sub-prime loans to an underdeveloped and insufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwrite and repack these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, banks were short on capital reserves and passed this chaos on to the repacked mortgages they had sold, and ultimately to the rest of the economy.

The roots of the financial crisis can be traced back to 1999 during the Clinton administration, as the President was aiming for a second term. He sought to boost his popularity by easing lending restrictions, setting the stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's largest mortgage underwriter, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans to low and moderate-income people and felt pressure from shareholders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes accurately predicted the consequences of these actions: “However, the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the economy's collapse.

Many factors combined to send the economy into freefall, one of which was the complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, further intertwining various sectors of the economy with the housing market. This led to U.S. households and financial markets overleveraging in the housing market, making them extremely vulnerable to even small price changes.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were caught off guard. The top five U.S. investment banks together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the U.S.'s GDP. In the end, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, die Exposition. Dieser Abschnitt in deiner Geschichte, wo du deine kleinen Schriftstellerflügel ausbreitest und abhebst, um alle mit deinem magnetischen, ja magischen Prosa zu beeindrucken. Oder der Teil, in dem deine Leser einschlafen oder auf die "Zurück" -Taste drücken und deinen Namen verfluchen. Dr. Merlin hat es schon erlebt, dass sie ihren Monitor anschreit, wenn sie sich in der Mitte von "Too Much Information" wiederfindet, und das auch nicht auf die schöne Art.

Exposition ist dein Feind.

Deine lieben Leser kennen schon den grundlegenden Schreibratgeber "Show, don't tell," aber Dr. Merlin stolpert immer wieder in lange Textpassagen, in denen nichts passiert oder noch Schlimmeres. Exposition ist der kleine Teufel auf deiner Schulter, der dir sagt, dass du die Vergangenheit beiseitelegen sollst, um zu den guten Teilen zu gelangen (nicht zu verwechseln mit dem kleinen Teufel auf der anderen Schulter, der dir befiehlt, deinem Publikum jede Einzelheit aus den Kindertagen jedes Charakters zu erzählen).

Exposition bedeutet, dem Publikum zu erzählen, was passiert ist, normalerweise in einfacher Prosa. Im Film passiert die Exposition, wenn ein Charakter einem anderen eine Kernausgabe von Informationen gibt, wie z.B. "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." Im Fiktionalen tut der Autor das Erzählen.

Ein Beispiel ist passend. Wenn du eine Geschichte liest, erfährst du, dass die Heldin ihren geliebten Mann an einem bestimmten Ort und zu einer bestimmten Zeit getroffen hat, dass sie in einer prunkvollen Weise verheiratet wurden und dass ihr Mann vor ihren Augen ermordet wurde. Du würdest nicht erwarten, dass diese ganze Sequenz zwei Seiten füllt, während beide jeweils nur zwei Zeilen Dialog haben. Du würdest erwarten, dass der Autor Zeit auf die Charakterisierung des Ehemanns verwendet, indem er durch seine Sprache und sein Benehmen zeigt, wie sehr er seine Frau liebt, und du würdest ebenfalls erwarten, dass die Heldin auf große und kleine Weise zeigt, wie seine Gegenwart in ihrem Leben sie verändert und bereichert hat (insbesondere wenn die Geschichte später direkt erzählt, dass dies der Fall war). Eine angemessene Einführung in den Ehemann würde dir ermöglichen, emotional an seinem Schicksal teilzuhaben und Einblicke in die Charaktere der Heldin zu gewinnen: Was sie in ihm sah, wie tief ihre Bindung war, Hinweise auf ihre Gedanken und Überzeugungen und Träume, die durch seine Augen reflektiert wurden, und so weiter. Du würdest an seinem Tod mit ihr leiden und dich so mit der Heldin verbinden.

Kurz gesagt, du erwartest Fleisch am simplen Knochen der Geschichte: "Sie trafen sich, sie heirateten, er starb."

Als Schriftsteller musst du dieses Fleisch bereiten. (*schaut auf das metaphorische Bild, seufzt, stürzt sich weiter*) Manchmal ist es verlockend, bestimmte Dinge zu übergehen. Vielleicht stellst du einem neuen Charakter vor, und du weißt, dass er früher bei der Air Force war und jetzt der Nachtmanager einer Tankstelle ist, und er war zweimal verheiratet, keine Kinder, mag es, am Wochenende angeln zu gehen, träumt im Geheimen davon, die Tankstelle eines Tages zu besitzen und hatte für das Frühstück Eier Benedict.

Ich habe zwei Nachrichten aus Columbus, Ohio verfolgt. Die erste, die „live“ war, war NBC 4 heute Morgen (August 13, 2011). Die Hauptnachricht handelte von einem Mann in Ashley, Ohio, der seine Frau mit einem Messer angegriffen hatte. Sie nannten seinen Namen, Shad Hostettler, aber nicht den seiner Frau. Sie zeigten sein Foto und er sah aus wie das pure Böse. Sie widmeten dem Fall nur etwa zwei Minuten, da er sich noch entwickelte. Die einzigen Details, die sie lieferten, waren, dass er sie mehrfach gestochen hatte und verhaftet worden war. Ich denke, sie haben eine angemessene Zeit für diese Geschichte reserviert.

Die zweite Geschichte handelte von einem frühen Morgenüberfall auf Travis Buyers, 18 Jahre alt. Er wurde im Sharon Woods Bereich angeschossen und schwer verletzt; es gab zu dem Zeitpunkt keine Festnahmen oder Verdächtige. Die SWAT-Einheit untersuchte den Vorfall. Diese Geschichte schien kurz zu sein und ich glaube, das könnte daran liegen, dass es sich um eine Geschichte aus einem „schwarzen“ Viertel handelte. Ich habe (und habe das schon seit Jahren) bemerkt, dass Minderheiten, wenn sie Opfer eines Verbrechens werden, oft übersehen werden. Wenn zum Beispiel ein „weißes“ Kind oder Erwachsener entführt oder ein Opfer eines Verbrechens ist, geht das Medium durch die Decke; aber wenn es sich um eine Person aus einer Minderheit handelt, ist es schon gut, wenn es überhaupt erwähnt wird.

Die nächste Geschichte handelte von einem Schussloch in einem Med-Flight-Hubschrauber. Details darüber, wo es passiert sein könnte, wurden gegeben. Es stellte sich heraus, dass es ein .22-Kaliber-Geschoss aus einem Gewehr war, das den Hubschrauber getroffen hatte. Crime-Stoppers bieten einen Finderlohn von 5000 Dollar für Hinweise an, die zur Festnahme des Schützen führen. Die nächste Geschichte betraf den Regen und die Gewitter, die für den Samstagnachmittag vorhergesagt wurden. Sie sagten, die Temperaturen würden im Wochenende im Mittelfeld der Achtziger liegen. Die Zeit, die sie dafür einplannten, war ein wenig kurz, aber sie wollten es als „Teaser“ verwenden, damit man weiter zuschaut.

Sie brachten auch eine Geschichte über einen Überfall auf einen Clime Road UDF in Columbus. Sie sagten, es sei ein dunkler, schwarzer Mann gewesen, der den Laden überfallen hatte. Er trug eine Kapuzenjacke. Sie sagten, er sei etwa sechs Fuß groß und wog etwa 150 Pfund. Ich fand, sie haben eine ungewöhnliche Menge Zeit darauf verwendet, zu betonen, dass er schwarz war und wie dunkel er war.

Eine weitere Geschichte handelte von einem René Rodriguez, der ein texanischer Drogenboss war. Er war wegen des Versuchs, in großen Mengen Marihuana aus Texas nach Ohio zu liefern, zu 25 Jahren Haft verurteilt worden. Ein seltsamer Punkt, den ich bemerkt habe, war, dass sie anstelle von „25 Jahren“ sagten „300 Monate“. Ich bin mir nicht sicher, ob sie dachten, das würde härter klingen oder was der Grund dafür war. Sie erwähnten auch, dass er ein Hispanic war, und ich denke, das war nicht wirklich relevant für die Geschichte.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within this bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, to name a few. Brothers understand each other more than anyone else can, and they see themselves reflected in their brothers. It's in the most trying moments that this bond truly shines, whether it's for good or ill. When these emotions are laid bare, they come at a great cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal connection is dealing with the consequences they bring. When one looks into the eyes of their brother and sees their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions, their true character is revealed. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers explore this theme and all the accompanying intense emotions. Against a backdrop of lush, vividly described landscapes, these two boys embark on a futile journey. Bitterness and disappointment crash against fierce pride in the pivotal scene, and only one brother makes it out alive. The theme is conveyed through the direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator's perspective, which conveys the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and their view of the world around them, both of which significantly influence their actions.

The human brain is a complex, creative information-processing system. As technology evolved from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also evolved. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.

Information processing begins with input from the sensory organs, which convert physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing combines very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the object's borders are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.

Once information is processed to a certain degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.

In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.

There are numerous models of how knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on human memory retrieval, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley kritisiert die bevorstehende Bedrohung sowohl durch Technologie als auch durch die kapitalistische Struktur, durch die letztere gefestigt wird, in seinem Roman Brave New World. Die Menschen legen Wert auf die Gemeinschaft über den Einzelnen und werden von Anfang an dazu konditioniert, das immediate Glück über alles andere zu streben. Die Bürger erweisen sich als Figuren in einem größeren Spiel, die in einer Ideologie gefangen sind, die vom World Controller festgelegt wird. Durch die Betrachtung des Werkes unter marxistischer Perspektive zeigt sich der Autor’s Verdacht an den Entwicklungen dieser Systeme. Begriffe wie Homogenität und Reifikation, die häufig in Marxismus verwendet werden, verstärken die Idee, dass Huxley’s Roman eine Kommentierung der Mängel der aufkommenden Wirtschaft aus seiner Zeit ist.

Kapitalismus wird durch die Verwendung des marxistischen Thesen der falschen Bewusstsein satirisiert. Im Wesentlichen werden die Menschen daran gehindert, die wahren Beziehungen zu anderen Klassen in wirtschaftlichen Begriffen zu erkennen, da sie hauptsächlich an ihrem eigenen Vorteil interessiert sind. Dies ist das Ergebnis der ideologischen Kontrolle des Proletariats und der Arbeiterklasse, was durch die Konditionierung der Menschen in Brave New World evident wird. Die gewöhnlichen Klassen, Delta, Gamma und andere, haben keinen eigenen Willen; durch Hypnopädie wird der Antrieb zum Konsum, zum Ausgeben, zum Übermaß gestärkt. Dies wird, wie bereits erwähnt, vom World Controller manipuliert. Hegemonie, also die Idee, dass Gruppen sozialer Klassen von einer separaten Gruppe vollständig dominiert werden, ist hier offensichtlich. Die unteren Klassen sind sich der Manipulation nicht bewusst, sondern "kaufen" tatsächlich in eine Ideologie, die diese Struktur unterstützt (das heißt Kapitalismus und Konsumismus). Die oberen Klassen geboren mit der Fähigkeit, dies zu erkennen, tun jedoch nichts; fast keine Alphas oder Betas tun mehr als dorthin zu gehören. In Wirklichkeit sind die Interaktionen der sozialen Klassen als solche Musterbeispiele für die Wahrnehmung der Kapitalismus bedingten Unterdrückung.

In Brave New World gibt es keine Beziehungen zwischen disparaten Individuen. Der Roman scheint die Charaktere nicht zu unterscheiden – nicht einmal bei den Hauptfiguren fehlt es an Tiefe. Vielleicht möchte Huxley damit sagen, dass die Aufstiege von Technologie und Kapitalismus zusammen den Menschen ihre Freiheit und Ausdrucksweise nehmen. Liebe existiert nicht, noch gibt es die Extreme einer einzigen Emotion; eher sind Interaktionen oberflächlich, was durch die Kommentare der Männer über Frauen, die sich hauptsächlich auf ihre physische Attraktivität beziehen, und die unverhohlenen Kommentare der Frauen über ihre Begegnungen, sozusagen, deutlich wird. Darüber hinaus zeigt die Zufriedenheit jeder gesellschaftlichen Klasse mit ihrem Status in der Hierarchie den soziologischen Effekt des Kapitalismus. Ihre absolute Unterordnung in der Gemeinschaft ist ein Zeichen des Marxismus über die Proletarier, die irrtümlich ihrer eigenen Überlegenheit über alles andere versichert sind, solange sie konsumieren, gehorchen und mit den anderen Schritt halten.

I've been a student at University Park for approximately two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. For many students, including myself, navigating the campus can be quite challenging. During my freshman year, I was housed in an East Halls dorm, essentially the easternmost point of campus, aside from the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in locations as distant as the Willard Building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes, especially on days with bad weather, which is common in State College. Speaking to an alumni not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the school by large tracts of unused land. Today, this empty space is filled with sports fields, new buildings like the new Creamery and health services center, and surrounded by apartments. As our campus continues to expand, navigating from one place to another becomes increasingly difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. However, a bike alone won't solve any problems; students need to use them, and the campus infrastructure must cater to cyclists.

I recently spoke with a friend who had resumed cycling after several years. He mentioned that he couldn't understand why he had ever stopped. "Bikes are great," he said, "for a few years it wasn't cool to ride a bike, but it's the most efficient way to get around." Apart from the health benefits, cycling is the most efficient mode of transportation. A bowl of oatmeal and some physical exertion can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus, as far from the center as some dorms. The best decision I made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have a class in Thomas Building, which is a 25-minute walk from my home. Riding my bike can reduce that time to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only issue is that Pollock Road is the most direct route to Thomas Building from my home, and it isn't always easy to travel on, whether by bike or on foot. While walking has its merits, I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would add an extra 30-40 minutes to my day, totaling over two and a half hours each week. Add to that the time spent walking to other classes, appointments, and more. That’s more time than I can spare.
